This paper deals with the problem of interference attacks in wireless networks, which is a common issue in the field of network security and communication. The paper specifically focuses on the physical layer attack in peer-to-peer networks, which falls under the category of network security and cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the use of game theory to develop anti-jamming strategies, which is a topic commonly studied in the field of networking and information theory (cs.NI and cs.IT). Additionally, the paper proposes a mechanism of maxmin selection for an attack prevention strategy, which is a concept often used in the field of control systems and system theory (cs.SY). Finally, the paper discusses the problem of incomparable metrics for measuring the effectiveness of an attack, which is a topic commonly studied in the field of graph theory and optimization (cs.GT).
